1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,929
Often we blame luck for our setbacks.

2
00:00:02,960 --> 00:00:07,490
We say, well, that's the way the ball bounces, and let it go at that.

3
00:00:07,600 --> 00:00:09,090
But stop and think.

4
00:00:09,440 --> 00:00:13,810
Balls don't bounce in certain ways for uncertain reasons.

5
00:00:14,080 --> 00:00:19,570
The bounce of a ball is determined by three things, the ball, the way it is thrown,

6
00:00:19,600 --> 00:00:21,490
and the surface it strikes.

7
00:00:21,840 --> 00:00:26,449
Definite physical laws explain the bounce of a ball, not luck.

8
00:00:27,040 --> 00:00:32,929
Suppose the CAA were to issue a report saying, we're sorry the crash occurred,

9
00:00:32,929 --> 00:00:35,969
but folks, that's just the way the ball bounces.

10
00:00:36,320 --> 00:00:39,169
You'd say it's time to get a new CAA.

11
00:00:39,200 --> 00:00:45,330
Or suppose a doctor explained to a relative, I'm awfully sorry, I don't know what happened.

12
00:00:45,360 --> 00:00:47,409
It's just one of those things.

13
00:00:47,760 --> 00:00:51,969
You'd switch doctors when you or another relative became ill.

14
00:00:52,720 --> 00:00:56,770
The that's the way the ball bounces approach teaches us nothing.

15
00:00:57,040 --> 00:01:03,729
We are no better prepared to avoid a duplication of the mistake the next time we face a similar situation.

16
00:01:04,080 --> 00:01:09,969
The football coach who takes Saturday's loss with, well boys, that's the way the ball bounces,

17
00:01:10,080 --> 00:01:14,290
isn't helping his team avoid the same mistakes the next Saturday.

18
00:01:15,360 --> 00:01:25,890
Orville Hubbard, mayor of Dearborn, Michigan for 17 consecutive years, is one of the nation's most colorful and respected urban administrators.

19
00:01:26,560 --> 00:01:35,010
For ten years prior to becoming mayor of Dearborn, Mr. Hubbard could have used the bad luck excuse and stepped out of politics.

20
00:01:35,760 --> 00:01:43,729
Before becoming a perennial winner, Orville Hubbard was unlucky three times in trying to get the nomination for mayor.

21
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:48,449
Three times he tried to get the nomination for state senator but failed.

22
00:01:48,720 --> 00:01:52,530
Once he was beaten in a race for a congressional nomination.

23
00:01:52,960 --> 00:01:55,890
But Orville Hubbard studied these setbacks.

24
00:01:56,080 --> 00:01:59,490
He regarded them as part of his political education.

25
00:01:59,679 --> 00:02:05,490
And today, he is one of the sharpest, most unbeatable politicians in local government.

26
00:02:06,080 --> 00:02:09,969
Instead of blaming luck, research those setbacks.

27
00:02:10,159 --> 00:02:12,050
If you lose, learn.

28
00:02:12,320 --> 00:02:20,050
Lots of folks go through life explaining their mediocrity with hard luck, tough luck, sour luck, bad luck.

29
00:02:20,640 --> 00:02:25,090
These people are still like children, immature, searching for sympathy.

30
00:02:25,280 --> 00:02:31,649
Without realizing it, they fail to see opportunities to grow bigger, stronger, more self-reliant.

31
00:02:32,159 --> 00:02:33,810
Stop blaming luck.

32
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:37,570
Blaming luck never got anyone where he wanted to go.

33
00:02:39,440 --> 00:02:48,209
A friend, who is a literary consultant, writer, and critic, chatted with me recently about what it takes to be a successful writer.

34
00:02:48,720 --> 00:02:54,290
A lot of would-be writers, he explained, simply aren't serious about wanting to write.

35
00:02:54,480 --> 00:02:59,729
They try for a little while but give it up when they discover there is real work involved.

36
00:03:00,159 --> 00:03:06,050
I haven't much patience with these people because they're looking for a shortcut and there just isn't one.

37
00:03:06,480 --> 00:03:11,409
But, he went on, I don't want to imply that pure persistence is enough.

38
00:03:11,600 --> 00:03:14,209
The plain truth is, often it isn't.

39
00:03:15,120 --> 00:03:21,649
Just now, I'm working with a fellow who's written 62 short fiction pieces but hasn't sold one.

40
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:25,968
Obviously, he is persistent in his goal to become a writer.

41
00:03:26,080 --> 00:03:31,570
But this fellow's problem is that he uses the same basic approach in everything he writes.

42
00:03:31,840 --> 00:03:34,465
He's developed a hard format for his stories.
